  "concept": "You can name people (Unit 4) and say what they like (Unit 5). Now describe them. The key skill is the French adjective — and its one big rule: it AGREES with the noun it describes.\n\nFeminine usually adds -e, and that often wakes up a final consonant: grand -> grande, petit -> petite, intelligent -> intelligente. Plural adds -s: grands, petites. Some adjectives already end in -e and don't change for gender (jeune, timide, drôle, sympa); a few are irregular (beau -> belle, gentil -> gentille).\n\nUse them most simply after être, where word order isn't an issue: « Elle est grande. », « Il est timide. » Add très (very) to turn it up: « Marie est très intelligente. »\n\nPlacement (for later): most French adjectives come AFTER the noun (un livre intéressant), but a handful of very common ones come before — grand, petit, beau, jeune, bon, joli (une petite fille). For now, lean on être and you can sidestep this.\n\nTwo more tools. To introduce someone, French prefers c'est + article + noun, not « il est »: « C'est un ami. », « C'est une fille sympa. » But for a bare adjective, use il/elle est: « Il est sympa. » And for looks, French says someone HAS hair, with avoir: « Il a les cheveux bruns. », « Elle a les cheveux blonds. »\n\nDescribe two people you know out loud, using être, one adjective each, and the correct agreement.",
